What is Dependency Injection (DI) in C#?
Dependency injection is a software design pattern that helps to reduce code complexity by allowing the dependency between objects to be injected at run time. It allows for looser coupling and makes it easier to test and maintain your code. Injection can occur either manually or through automated means. This article explains how to implement dependency injection in C# using AutoWiring and IoC containers.
Why would you use Dependency Injection?
There are many reasons why you might want to use DI, including:
Reduced code complexity – by abstracting away dependencies, you can reduce the amount of code needed to use a particular object.
Looser coupling – because you're not tightly coupling your class to its dependencies, you have more flexibility to change them later.
Easier testing – since you don't need to create mock objects, you can easily test your classes without worrying about their dependencies.
More reusable code – if you extract an object's dependencies into a container, you can easily share that object across multiple applications.
What's the difference between Manual Dependency Injection and Automated Dependency Injection?
With manual dependency injection, you specify which objects should be injected at runtime. For example, you might have a method that takes an ILogger as an argument:
public void DoSomething(ILogger logger)
{
    // do something with the logger...
}
